<Page
    x:Name="page1"
    x:Class="ColorMixer.Pages.HomePage"
    DataContext="{Binding DefaultViewModel, RelativeSource={RelativeSource Self}}"
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
    xmlns:local="using:ColorMixer.Pages"
    xmlns:common="using:ColorMixer.Common"
    xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
    xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
    mc:Ignorable="d">

    <!--
        This grid acts as a root panel for the page that defines two rows:
        * Row 0 contains the page title
        * Row 1 contains the rest of the page layout
    -->
    <Grid Background="{ThemeResource ApplicationPageBackgroundThemeBrush}">
        <Grid.ChildrenTransitions>
            <TransitionCollection>
                <EntranceThemeTransition/>
            </TransitionCollection>
        </Grid.ChildrenTransitions>
        <Grid.RowDefinitions>
            <RowDefinition Height="140"/>
            <RowDefinition Height="*"/>
        </Grid.RowDefinitions>

        <!-- Back button and page title -->
        <Grid Grid.Row="0">
            <Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
                <ColumnDefinition Width="120"/>
                <ColumnDefinition Width="*"/>
            </Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
            <Image 
                Grid.Column="0"
                x:Name="logoimage" 
                HorizontalAlignment="Center" 
                Height="100" 
                VerticalAlignment="Center" 
                Width="100" 
                Source="ms-appx:///Assets/square70logo.png" 
                IsHitTestVisible="False"/>
            <TextBlock 
                Grid.Column="1" 
                Text="Windows Developer Content: ColorMixer" 
                Style="{StaticResource HeaderTextBlockStyle}" 
                x:Uid="AppName" 
                x:Name="pageTitle" 
                IsHitTestVisible="False" 
                TextWrapping="NoWrap" 
                VerticalAlignment="Center"/>
        </Grid>
        <Grid Grid.Row="1">
            <Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
                <ColumnDefinition Width="120"/>
                <ColumnDefinition Width="*"/>
            </Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
            <StackPanel Grid.Column="1">
                <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource TitleTextStyle}" Text="Intro" x:Uid="Page1Intro"></TextBlock>
                <RichTextBlock Style="{StaticResource BodyRichTextBlockStyle}" >
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        While other operating systems focus primarily on touch input, Windows enables you to build the kind of app you want without constraints: consumption apps, productivity apps, or innovative hybrid apps on PCs, laptops, tablets and pretty much any form factor out there (and even some that aren’t quite there yet).
                    </Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        This is the companion sample for the User interaction customization, start to finish topics (
                        <Hyperlink NavigateUri="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=329868">HTML</Hyperlink> and
                        <Hyperlink NavigateUri="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=389067">XAML</Hyperlink>).
                    </Paragraph>
                </RichTextBlock>
                <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource TitleTextStyle}">
                    <LineBreak/>
                    Description
                </TextBlock>
                <RichTextBlock Style="{StaticResource BodyRichTextBlockStyle}" >
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        Customize the user interaction experiences in your Windows Store app based on input from various sources (including touch, touchpad, mouse, pen/stylus, and keyboard) and input-device modes (such as touch keyboard, mouse wheel, and pen eraser). The sample follows Windows 8.1 principles, recommendations, and implementation details for custom controls, UI accessibility, and customized interactions.
                    </Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        In the sample, we create a color mixer in the form of a square object that takes direct input from a touch screen, touchpad, mouse, pen/stylus, or keyboard. It uses this data to specify an RGB color and an angle of rotation, which it translates to a corresponding red, green, or blue level.
                    </Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        <Bold>Note</Bold>
                        We recommend that you use the platform control libraries (
                        <Hyperlink NavigateUri="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=389074">HTML</Hyperlink> and
                        <Hyperlink NavigateUri="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=389073">XAML</Hyperlink>) wherever possible. 
                        The controls in these libraries provide the full Windows 8.1 user interaction experience, 
                        including standard interactions, animated physics effects, visual feedback, and accessibility. 
                        If you don't need customized interaction support, use these built-in controls.
                    </Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        This app is based on the
                        <Hyperlink NavigateUri="http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=325593">Flat navigation sample</Hyperlink> and meets all basic Windows Store certification requirements and covers:</Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph TextIndent="50">• Custom controls</Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph TextIndent="50">• Handling input from various input devices</Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph TextIndent="50">• Designing interactions based on Windows user interaction guidelines</Paragraph>
                    <Paragraph TextIndent="50">• Processing pointer and gesture input</Paragraph>
                    <!-- Don't use a button when the action is to go to another page;
                    use direct links within the content or the nav bar to move between pages.
                    See Guidelines and checklist for buttons at http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=313598 -->
                    <Paragraph>
                        <LineBreak/>
                        <Hyperlink 
                            x:Name="linkColorMixerXAML" Click="linkColorMixerXAML_Click">ColorMixer (XAML)</Hyperlink> || 
                        <Hyperlink 
                            x:Name="linkColorMixerWinRT" Click="linkColorMixerWinRT_Click">ColorMixer (WinRT)</Hyperlink>
                    </Paragraph>
                </RichTextBlock>
            </StackPanel>
        </Grid>
    </Grid>
</Page>
